<subSubSection id="CC7133FAE290875CB6408B52CFC3B2F3" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B12AD1EA7384FEF3E9B4767F912A7D2" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="66B2577ED05D1DB60CE40E3521BD2222" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Antenna with scape, pedicel and F1 yellow and rest of flagellomeres dark brown. Scutellum with median groove in approximately anterior 1/2. Legs mostly yellowish with fore and hind coxae yellowish white. Gaster yellowish except margins brown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="40F83DC8C38F88D6FC1EFBDD369883A6" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" type="description">
<paragraph id="F4802D8CF1C65019279D8417CBA7A7B9" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DC6A8838092FBFAB0FD2051F57E89324" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
<emphasis id="EC6CDC85D96E001183BAC7977BCE05E3" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Female.</emphasis>
Body length 1.9 mm, fore wing length 1.3 mm. Body yellow. Mandibles yellow with teeth brown. Antenna with scape, pedicel, and F1 yellow and remainder of flagellomeres dark brown. Legs mostly yellowish except fore and hind coxae yellowish white. Gaster yellowish except margins brown. Ovipositor black.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="4A3516D13DEC0E8549D149B50D2F588C" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
<emphasis id="EF1E905681F35B193DB081258785BE7D" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Head</emphasis>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="EA91CB2243D57329EE4D29518EECA700" captionStart="Figures 5–10" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 5 - 10. D. fossa sp. nov., female, holotype 5 habitus in dorsal view 6 antenna 7 fore wing 8 hind wing 9 habitus in lateral view 10 head in frontal view. Scale bars: 100 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.80671.figures5-10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671712" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">10</figureCitation>
) 1.3
<normalizedToken id="AD7BDE96E25038426F3ED1DF2FD28A1F" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as wide as high in frontal view and ~ 2.3
<normalizedToken id="A01F6E684D273D469D4BFF91AE984E04" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as wide as long in dorsal view. Lower face and vertex transversely reticulate, frons weakly sculptured. POL 2.4
<normalizedToken id="DECAE4EA84110D073FA6C0CD5EB6DAEA" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
OOL. Malar space 0.4
<normalizedToken id="E373C004C9CE9B939381381B28BCDCAE" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
eye height. Occiput weakly reticulate. Relative measurements (length: width): scape = 35: 6; pedicel = 11: 6; F1 = 19: 6; F2 = 12: 7; F3 =13: 8; F4 = 12: 8; clava = 20: 8.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="767F362C81FF6D841ADEECF014011425" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
<emphasis id="CD796D3C522450B7764B6397CFAE992D" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Mesosoma</emphasis>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="1BCDF174F6EDC328194CFED3EFCCD560" captionStart="Figures 5–10" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 5 - 10. D. fossa sp. nov., female, holotype 5 habitus in dorsal view 6 antenna 7 fore wing 8 hind wing 9 habitus in lateral view 10 head in frontal view. Scale bars: 100 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.80671.figures5-10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671712" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">5</figureCitation>
). Midlobe of mesoscutum punctate with three pairs of long setae, lateral lobe of mesoscutum reticulate. Notauli ending laterad to inner angles of axilla. Axillae weakly reticulate and separated from each other. Scutellum with median groove in approximately anterior 1/2 and two pairs of long setae, sublateral grooves meet posteriorly. Spiracle with a transverse carina anteriorly, separated from metanotum by a distance almost as long as a diameter of spiracle; each propodeal callus with six setae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D440C6C7A43F13C524363D321A730363" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
<emphasis id="F56E9ABD086A74B68934283D4967EB9D" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
<emphasis id="70DEDB66AD93304EB2DAE7C2A02D2B5F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Wings</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Fore wing (Figs 
<figureCitation id="5FFB90204FFB06CFC2ED9E0100904051" captionStart="Figures 5–10" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 5 - 10. D. fossa sp. nov., female, holotype 5 habitus in dorsal view 6 antenna 7 fore wing 8 hind wing 9 habitus in lateral view 10 head in frontal view. Scale bars: 100 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.80671.figures5-10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671712" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">5</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="73291F8A6A199924C1726E6D4CAC449C" captionStart="Figures 5–10" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 5 - 10. D. fossa sp. nov., female, holotype 5 habitus in dorsal view 6 antenna 7 fore wing 8 hind wing 9 habitus in lateral view 10 head in frontal view. Scale bars: 100 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.80671.figures5-10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671712" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">7</figureCitation>
) 2.6
<normalizedToken id="33F0FB57F5FA1BC661B8E2F5AEBB3F72" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as wide. Relative measurements (length): SMV = 33; MV= 45; PMV= 17; STV= 12. Hind wing (Figs 
<figureCitation id="E4C3240CDBE23BE2DD89EE5F6C1C81C9" captionStart="Figures 5–10" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 5 - 10. D. fossa sp. nov., female, holotype 5 habitus in dorsal view 6 antenna 7 fore wing 8 hind wing 9 habitus in lateral view 10 head in frontal view. Scale bars: 100 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.80671.figures5-10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671712" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">5</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="70383704DC5D6935C2580F6EE29D9195" captionStart="Figures 5–10" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 5 - 10. D. fossa sp. nov., female, holotype 5 habitus in dorsal view 6 antenna 7 fore wing 8 hind wing 9 habitus in lateral view 10 head in frontal view. Scale bars: 100 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.80671.figures5-10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671712" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">8</figureCitation>
) ~ 4.5
<normalizedToken id="EC20DA7FDBEE1F5258FE281B184A3F36" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as wide.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D3E0C3EF74BF73A22CCD106F9A7AA354" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
<emphasis id="F232062A9CBFAED220F4E757A1860394" bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Metasoma</emphasis>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation id="B6FE844B5B7FA102C339FC925981B1C3" captionStart="Figures 5–10" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figures 5 - 10. D. fossa sp. nov., female, holotype 5 habitus in dorsal view 6 antenna 7 fore wing 8 hind wing 9 habitus in lateral view 10 head in frontal view. Scale bars: 100 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1095.80671.figures5-10" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/671712" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">5</figureCitation>
). Gaster ovate, 1.7
<normalizedToken id="092C55E503ECBE44945465B3653BF234" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as wide, and 1.2
<normalizedToken id="26EE53EF647C7457CD092CB3BFF73904" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as along as mesosoma. Ovipositor exserted beyond apex of gaster.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F1F4C46457050F1246D6619B789A1FE3" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
<emphasis id="369867092CFE0BC029085CE729818280" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Male.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1ADBAC0A1FB3493602EC93BE830F42E8" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" type="host">
<paragraph id="A2048374B951983C6A79FA249116FBD0" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Host.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3C20775AE9383CA4F31C9225E386443F" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CBE6020CA80CD605960632CEBEB57019" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="B01FD694FC4447360D5C204B51A3AD4F" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="ABC8C288E15D2A292F9633EE4388FC07" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">China (Shandong).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="EE80D99A03F2A920E2C0B00B1E063F3A" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="6CF28C797D5D094DD175A0EF95C00AA2" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2F4C25D6B9A0CE65A5BED9667740E1F0" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
Latin: 
<emphasis id="39F8E9BD7AB521B5302A2E8C0A6754A2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">fossa</emphasis>
= ditch, trench; and refers to the median groove in the approximate anterior 1/2 of scutellum.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3B26BC7A7C9112B68BD693E212CAC0FB" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="35DFC7CB95755A40022F1DDC2FBF8FEE" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F9A70E144E4D84CA2BA1BE7642FE6AFB" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">
<taxonomicName id="8EDD5872ECC86E2AB842C310C31B08D2" authorityName="Fan &amp; Li" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Eulophidae" genus="Diglyphomorphomyia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Diglyphomorphomyia fossa" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fossa">
<emphasis id="53EF3CCDD742CB5C8C93C466B1184455" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">Diglyphomorphomyia fossa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="5EE934B8AB2EE9012D9EF708F68C9FF7" class="Insecta" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. aequus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aequus">
<emphasis id="C23CD154F417C41BBD9027A6A84339D6" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">D. aequus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Zhu &amp; Huang, 2003 in sharing the antenna with a yellow scape, pedicel, and F1, while the remaining segments are brown; and the notauli straight and converging posteriorly to meet laterad to inner angles of axillae, but the new species can be separated from 
<taxonomicName id="FFCBE3DB74D548A6EE17C980ABAE415E" class="Insecta" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. aequus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aequus">
<emphasis id="1720FA250AC5854E62E969371A4CF468" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">D. aequus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the following combination of characters: legs yellowish with fore and hind coxae yellowish white (legs yellow in 
<taxonomicName id="0500155C47D82695925605B0C9BF6E7A" class="Insecta" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. aequus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aequus">
<emphasis id="201067A833A72DA60B0C04BC20BFB167" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">D. aequus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); gaster yellowish except margins brown (gaster yellow with a brown patch in 
<taxonomicName id="A9C67C46EEF0898A3C5C1E869360310A" class="Insecta" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. aequus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="111" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aequus">
<emphasis id="403B7D33993C070C73AFF18C9AC5E6CC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="111">D. aequus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); gaster 1.7
